                                                                                                                           6                                                                                      More from Merc 
          OUR CORRESPONDENT                      Wilfried Aulbur in New Delhi on Thursday. Picture by Prem Singh				                                 
	New Delhi, Jan. 28: Mercedes Benz India today rolled out a new version of its luxury sedan S350 in petrol and diesel variants. The company plans to introduce some more vehicles in the first quarter of the next fiscal.        
	Globally the S-Class is an overwhelming market leader in its segment as well as in India with over 53 per cent share of the market ... The new S-Class will carry forward the leadership in the segment, said Wilfried Aulbur, managing director and CEO, Mercedes Benz India.        
	The petrol variant of the new S350 will be priced at Rs 82 lakh, while the diesel variant will carry a price tag of Rs 80.5 lakh (ex-showroom, Delhi).        
	The 2010 S-Class is able to see and feel, respond reflexively and act autonomously to prevent accidents or mitigate their effects, he said.        
	The car has features such as advance parking guidance with ultrasonic sensors, climatised seats and massage option for rear seats. The sedan also comes with the Splitview technology that allows simultaneous onscreen display of two different images on the instrument panel.         
	Later this year, Mercedes will launch the upgraded M-Class and the E-Coupe. At the Delhi auto expo Mercedes had showcased its saloon S500L, sports utility vehicle GL 350CDI and performance vehicle SLS AMG.         
	More cars are coming up next fiscal, we are expanding our reach in the country  we will have a strong double-digit growth in 2010, said Aulbur.        
	Aulbur said the company had invested about Rs 250 crore over the last one-and-half years in its plant and another Rs 150-200 crore in network expansion.                          
	Even though the company had lost leadership position in the premium segment in India to rival BMW and reported a decline of 10.43 per cent in sales in the country for the last year, Mercedes said it was looking at a strong double-digit growth in the current calendar year.                                                                                                                                      
